    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="120"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d120">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 182/19a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary to President <persName corresp="#p_WW1"
                            type="from">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi> (<persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Close</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">U. S. S. “George Washington,”</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-10">10 December,
                        1918</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Memorandum for the Secretary of State:</p>
                <p>The President asks if you will be kind enough to have for [<hi rend="italic"
                        >sic</hi>] following message sent in code to Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HCEM1">House</persName> in France: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Referring to your No. 19, December 9th, the President asks me to say
                            that while he greatly regrets the necessity for postponing the beginning
                            of the formal business of conference until the third or fourth of
                            January, he is of course willing to acquiesce in the programme as
                            outlined, subject of course to such changes as may be mutually agreeable
                            upon conference after his arrival. But he wishes <pb facs="0217" n="147"
                                xml:id="pg_147"/> me to ask if it would not be possible, in some
                            tactful way that would not give offence or be misunderstood, to avoid
                            the demonstration of laboring men and socialists which you say is being
                            planned for the afternoon of Saturday. The President fears embarrassment
                            from any seeming identification with any single element, and recalls the
                            criticisms already made by those interested in opposing his principles
                            with regard to the source of the popular support which he is
                            receiving.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>[For] The President <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">G. F. Close</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
